steakchaser:
We're also experiencing the same / similar issue when using redux and redux-form.  In our case, on first request, data is populated into the redux store, which redux-form uses to initialize itself.  Because the ExecJS context is "cached" via the rendering pool, the store with the data from the first request is then the starting point for all subsequent requests.
On subsequent requests, redux-form (5.3.3 in our case) thinks that it's already initialized uses the data from the cached context (first request).
To get around this, we are using reduce-reducers to gain access to the entire state tree and then dispatching a RESET_ALL action in the top-level componentWillMount to clear out the entire state:
```javascript
// root reducer
import { combineReducers } from 'redux'
import { reducer as form } from 'redux-form'
import reduceReducers from 'reduce-reducers'
import { RESET_ALL } from '../actions'
import sliceA from './slice-a-reducer'
import sliceB from './slice-b-reducer'
const reducer = combineReducers({
  sliceA,
  sliceB,
  form
})
const resetRootReducer = (state, action) => {
  switch(action.type) {
    case RESET_ALL : {
      return {}
    }
    default : return state;
  }
}
export default reduceReducers(reducer, resetRootReducer)
```
```javascript
// top-level component
import React, { Component, PropTypes } from 'react'
import { createStore, applyMiddleware } from 'redux'
import thunk from 'redux-thunk'
import { Provider } from 'react-redux'
import createLogger from 'redux-logger'
import { RESET_ALL } from '../actions'
import reducer from '../reducers'
let middlewares = [thunk]
if (process.env.NODE_ENV == 'development') {
  middlewares.push(createLogger())
}
const createStoreWithMiddleware = applyMiddleware(...middlewares)(createStore)
const store = createStoreWithMiddleware(reducer)
class App extends Component {
componentWillMount() {
    // Reset state
    store.dispatch({ type: RESET_ALL })
  }
render() {
    return (

    )
  }
}
export default App
```
We also experimented with keeping the redux stores in a global var (i.e. MyReduxStores) and dispatching the RESET_ALL action via a custom after_render string:
```ruby
lib/my_app/server_rendering/redux_safe_server_renderer.rb
module MyApp
  module ServerRendering
    class ReduxSafeServerRenderer < React::ServerRendering::SprocketsRenderer
  def after_render(component_name, props, prerender_options)
    <<-JS
      (function () {
        MyReduxStores.forEach(function(store) {
          store.dispatch({ type: 'RESET_ALL' })
        });
      })();
    JS
  end

end

end
end
```
Is there a better way to do this?  Curious if anyone else has encountered this and what type of approach they've taken?
